African leaders have committed to speed up carrying outi initiatives that have been identified or launched to build resilience against climate change damage.The leaders committed to use their countriesy resources and mobilise multilateral and bilateral donors as well as non-state actors.More than 30 African heads of state and government met yesterday in Marrakesh for the First Africa Action Summit, which was held on the sidelines of the 22nd Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change.President Uhuru Kenyatta (pictured) was among the leaders attending the summit. In a statement, he said development of the rulebook to guide implementation of the Paris Agreement must focus on its objective, principles and provisions of the convention, including equity and common good but differentiate responsibilities and respective capabilities. The process should also take into consideration the obligations of developed country parties to provide additional, predictable and sustainable support in terms of finance, technology and capacity building to meet the adaptation and mitigation needs of the developing country Parties, he said.Kenya has a climate change Act and a national adaptation plan, which contribute to the national implementation of the Paris Agreement.Through King of Morocco Mohammed VI, who chaired the summit, the leaders reaffirmed their commitment to contribute to global efforts to combat climate change.